        "A": "Implement a retry mechanism with exponential backoff in the agent code that attempts to invoke the MCP tool again if it fails initially.",
        "B": "Add an explicit instruction in the system prompt for the web search agent to always use the designated MCP tool when searching the web, even if it seems unnecessary.",
        "C": "Configure the MCP server to enable a 'tool enforcement' mode that ensures all matching queries are routed through the correct tools without exception.",
        "D": "Modify the tool description in the MCP configuration to include more detailed examples and edge cases to better match potential user inputs.",
    },
    "correct_answer": "C",
    "option_explanations": {
        "A": "While a retry mechanism can help with transient failures, it does not address the root cause of sporadic non-compliance by the model. This is an over-engineered solution that introduces additional complexity without ensuring deterministic behavior.",
        "B": "Relying on natural language prompts to enforce tool usage is unreliable and probabilistic. The model may or may not comply with such instructions, leading to inconsistent results. This approach does not provide a guaranteed fix for the issue.",
        "C": "Enabling 'tool enforcement' mode in the MCP configuration ensures that all matching queries are routed through the correct tools without exception. This provides deterministic guarantees and is the most effective mitigation strategy.",
        "D": "While refining tool descriptions can improve initial compliance, it does not guarantee consistent behavior across all edge cases or user inputs. The model may still occasionally fail to invoke the tool correctly due to probabilistic interpretation of prompts."
    },
    "explanation": "The correct answer is C because configuring the MCP server to enable 'tool enforcement' mode ensures deterministic routing of queries through designated tools, providing a reliable and consistent solution. Options A and B introduce additional complexity or rely on probabilistic model compliance rather than deterministic guarantees, while option D addresses only part of the issue without ensuring full consistency."
